<br>
Here goes:<br>
<br>
1)  What should we have done with regard to the Iran/Iraq war in the 1980s?  What we DID do was assure that neither country gained the upper hand, and we manipulated both sides to guarantee a stalemate in the conflict, because neither side had a stable government.  What do YOU think should have happened?<br>
<br>
2)  What did the UN do to mitigate that conflict? (Back this up with factual research please).  <br>
<br>
3)  What did FRANCE do to mitigate that conflict? (Again, research this please).<br>
<br>
4)  How long do you think we should wait until taking action against countries living under terroristic regimes who openly make threats against the United States?  Do you feel that we should only respond to these threats if they are acted upon, as in the case of the WTC bombings?  <br>
<br>
5)  Do you really believe that Saddam Hussein didn't know that an Al-Qaeda cell was operating in Northern Iraq against the Kurdish forces?  This one is easy, yes or no will suffice.<br>
<br>
6)  Do you feel that the US government and security agencies were lax in responding to terrorist warnings prior to the 9/11 attacks?  Do you think pre-emptive action could have prevented 3000 civilian deaths, or do you feel that the attack was inevitable?<br>
<br>
7)  Do you believe that free elections could ever exist under Saddam Hussein's regime?  Do you believe that the majority of Iraqis supported Hussein?  <br>
<br>
8]   Do you believe that Hussein would willingly surrender power to his population if they enacted nonviolent resistance?<br>
<br>
9)  Do you feel that the free Western world has an obligation to help socially and technologically underdeveloped countries and cultures?<br>
<br>
10)  This one is a three-parter:  Do you really feel that Hitler's main goal was survival and prosperity for his nation?  At what point, if any, do you think his nation achieved prosperity, and how does the extermination of the Jews contribute to German prosperity and survival?  Do you believe that the Holocaust never happened?<br>
<br>
11)  Who do you feel is qualified to lead the reconstruction in Iraq?  Please list corporations,  companies, or countries that you feel are viable candidates and list the reasons why you feel they are qualified.  <br>
<br>
12)  Do you feel that the U.S. should reduce military spending?  Do you think that we, as a nation, are secure and unthreatened at home and abroad, enough to justify cost-cuts across the board?  Please provide researched reasons and cite sources supporting why you feel one way or the other. <br>
<br>
13)  Do you believe that Bush Sr. and the U.S. government had enough global and internal American support to continue to push forward in Desert Storm instead of &quot;closing our wallets&quot; and hanging Iraqi allies out to dry?  <br>
<br>
14)  Do you feel that the UN is doing enough to combat terrorism, oppression, poverty, and starvation globally?  Please list instances where the UN has effectively prevented conflict or enacted change in corrupt regimes, anywhere in the world.<br>
<br>
15)  Do you feel that Colin Powell is qualified to be the American Secretary of State?  If not, whom do you believe would be a better candidate?  <br>
<br>
16)  At what point did Iraq provide support to our anti-terror effort?  Please provide documentation.  Please also document Hussein's comments on 9/11/01 applauding the World Trade Center attacks.<br>
<br>
17)  Do you believe that the comparison of Herman Goerring to George W. Bush is justified?  Are you aware that when Goerring's remarks about &quot;telling the people they are being attacked&quot; references Hitler's vilification of the Jews, and does not reference a direct military strike on pre-WW2 Germany?  Do you find jokes about Nazism funny?  Do you believe that comparing precision-guided munitions and an active attempt to minimize civilian casualties to rounding up millions of Jews and gassing them is a fair comparison? <br>
<br>
18]    Do you believe that the United States should remain in the United Nations, given our history of ignoring UN resolutions which do not favor us?  Do you believe that France's population size, landmass, and political and military influence justify its right to a Security Council veto?  <br>
<br>
19)  Have you ever been under direct fire?  Have you ever fired a weapon in self-defense?  Please provide examples.  <br>
<br>
20)  Do you believe that, given more time, the Baath party would have crumbled?  Do you think that Saddam Hussein's death of natural causes would have been the end of the party, or do you think one of his sons would have come to power?  Do you believe that the UN had the manpower capabilities to convincingly mount an effective inspection in a country the size of California with a vast network of underground tunnels?  <br>
<br>
There you go.  20 questions.  It will take you some time to formulate answers to those questions, but it will be time well-spent.  Please present them here in this thread, in a cogent and coherent manner.  Feel free to use EZBoard's spellcheck feature, but please be sure to credit your sources properly.  Pretend you're a college graduate writing an essay.  <br>
<br>
I'll be happy to answer any questions you have for me, provided that you actively participate, respectfully, in this dialogue.  I'll be more than happy to engage in a point/counterpoint discussion of these (and other) issues.  <br>
<br>
Since your earlier post consisted of nothing more than smileys and direct quotes of me, I can't really address it.  I will answer the one question you posed, however, regarding casualty figures from Hussein's regime.  My sources are Amnesty International and the International Human Rights Watch, both non-American independent nonprofit organizations.  Both put the casualties (only those casualties which occurred as a DIRECT RESULT of Hussein's orders) at between 400,000 and 500,000 civilians since 1988.  Those figures are deaths only, and do not account for non-fatal injuries or physical/psychological torture victims.       <br>
